. We wish you the\nvery speediest of recoveries, so\nthat you can have fun the rest of\nyour month's vacation. No doubt\nyou've proved yoursen to be as\ngood a patient as last time.\nMeeting\nAl! of you members are invit\ned to attend the meeting of our\nclub next Tuesday. Sept. 18, at\n8 P. M. .-tharp. We would like to\nsee\" everyuody attend\nro\nthat we\ncan discuss future activities.\nCAPITALCITY BITS\nBy Katy Gotzm\u00bb*ister\nColuuihus, O., Sept. 13- Here\nwe are oack in Colutmbus again\nafter spending a grand Labor\nDay -veekend in Salem. We go*\nback too late to have an article\nlast weekend, but wt want you\nSalemitfx* to know that wc have\nnot forgotten the swell time we\nhad in y/iur fair city. It sure was\n,grand to ee many \u00abinilar face\u00bb\nagain.\nToo bad w- couldn't visit the\nSaxon Club on Sunday eve tut\nwe h-ui ust as gootl a time at\nthe Romanian Hall, if not. even\nbetter. Ji was good singing thosa\ngood old songs again, especially\nwith our tall leader, who stood\nout amciigst us all at li.c table,\nnamely Tom Deptner from De\ntroit We also enjoyed the com\nmunity -ingirg at the picnic on\nMonday. After all thai vocalizing*\nover .he weekend, we were a ill\ntie hoarse Tuesday. P\u00bbvt it vva\nworth it. Thanks again Salem\nfor the f.rami time and we hope\nto see you all in Columbus soon.\nThe weekend ended all too\nsoon but a good times must com.\nto an end.\nBy the way Henry Hohnes\nhave you found tiu-t bW job that\nsomeone liked as will a\u00bb you\ndid? While looking\ntor\nyour car.\nif you happen to cot. e across a\nfoot of tread om a vre it be\nlongs to the car from Loiumbuj.\nLucky we had a sp.'.re or we\nneves would have gotttc home.\nNotice\nSaturday. Nov. 3, the dat\nchosen ia all you Juniors to at\ntend a good football ^ame. be\ntween Ohio State ana Northwes\ntern. Reserved seats for thi*\ngame a e $3.00 and General Ad\u00bb\nmission $1.50. We are betting\n9\ndeadline tor reservations. Oct,\n15th. So send your reservations\nfor football tickets and hotel ve\nservatior to:\n\u00a3v\u00ab4yii l'arr. 761 Gilbest St..\nvolutaibus 6, Ohio\nWhen Your\nBack Hurts-\nAnd Year Strength end\nEnergy\nIs\nBelow Par\nIt may be eauaad by dlaorder of Md\nBey function that parmlta poiaoaoue\nvaata to accumulate. For truly naw\npeople feel tired, weak and mlaerable\nvhea the kidneys fail to remove\nitiiim\nadds and other waste matter from the\nblood.\nYea may eeffer aagglng backache\nrheumatle peine, headachee, ilUiln\u2014.\ngetting ep nlghta, leg peine, welling.\nBorneomee frequent and scanty urlaa\ntlee with smarting and burning ia an\nother sign that something is wrong with\nthi kidneyi or bUddtr\u00ab\nThere would be aadoabt that yrempS\ntreatment ia wiaer than neglect. Use\nDoan'i FitU.\nIt ia better to lib on a\nmedicine that haa won countrywide ap\nproval than on something lees favorably\nknown.\nDoan'i\nhave bean tried and test\u00ad\ned many yeere. Are et all dreg stores.\nGet today.\nDDee*\nPills\noans\nnot later than October 15th. All\nreservations received any later\nwill not be accepted. We are try\ning to \u00a3Ct an entire section at\nthe game so we can all be to\ngether. This will be the main\ngame of Ohio State here in Co\nlumbus 'his year so get your re\nservations in early.\nThe Columbus Juniors will\nhave a dance that evening.Watch\nthis column for further details\nregarding this event.\nLet all your cars 1.x turned to,\nColumbus on Saturday, Nov. 3.\nO\nQUESTIONS?\nCongress Hard\nImportant\n\\nswers will be found rn page 7 jpsrres in ihe tropics, so- example,\nappear to be highly tesistant to\n1. How is time measured?\"\n2. VV hirh is heaviest\u2014gold,\nsilver or lead\n3. What is the most ancicht\nscience\n4. What is the !*rgtt planet\nin the scl.ii system\n5. The atomic weicht of any\nelement is found through com\nparison tvith the weight of an\natom of what element:\n6. Excpt for the sun and moon,\nwhat is the most brilliant ob jeer\nin the heavens 1\n7. What important v'oduce\ncomee f*om Cinnabar mines?\nAt It\nMrs. Bolton sion of the ad\nministration of\nthe sale of surplus property, se\nlective service extension and reor\nganization of government depart\nments. A limited tax revision is\nItlso a possibility.\nEmergency unemployment com\npensation may be the first acted\nupon as both the Ways and Means\nCommittee of the House and the\nFinance Committee of the Senate\nare working on legislation which\nWould include maritime and civil\nService employees in providing\nminimum benefits of $25 per week\nfor a half year\u201426 weeks.\n^CURTAILMENT of government\nwar activities is no simple\nproblem. Quite on the contrary,\nevery day since Japan capitulated\nhas brought additional knotty\nproblems. The following is an ex\nample: There is a general feeling\nthat the government should point\nthe way in \"reconversion\" by eli\nmir \".ting war agencies with a view\nto getting back to what is looked\nUpon as normal for the future. Not\nt. r^turr. to a pre-war basis, for\nthat cannot be. Changes have come\ndomestically as well as interna\nlonally\u2014new conditions, new re\nlations, new problems.\niJven in those cases where there\nif general agreement that agencies\nt-hoald be discontinued immediate\nly. that is not always possible. In\nthe maze of government agencies\naiiti bureaus that were set up prior\nto the war and during wartime\nare those established by law, and\niv.auy, many others created by exe\ncutive order, and it is the latter\nthat have the government lawyers\nin a quandary.\nWhere Congress established\nJUST HUMANS\n4M|, (JfUk\ns\nKnowledge Gained from\nAfar\n$he present pen\u00e9trfctfo* \u00e9f\nAmerican medical men to many\ncorners of the earth is expected\nto result in an increased knowl\nedge of the effect of race on the\nincidence and course of diseases\nin individuals of vatying racial\norigins. Present knowledge in\nthis field is defective and often\ncontradictory, according to \"The\nJournal of the Amercan Medical\nAssociation\". Clue: to affective\ntreatments, or preventative\nmeasures, for diseases acecting\nresidents of this country may be\nobtained from such studies. Ne-\ncancer of the skin, and the Ame\nrican Indians, Eskimos,^Chinese,\nJapanese and Coreans, all of si\nmilar Mongolian origin, have\nvery low blood pressure, while\nthe Filipinos, who are neighbor\ning Malays, have the higher\nblood pressures com noo \u00abinoiig\njphite persons.\n-4*--\nA vaccine to immunise cattle\nagainst yh^os-an-d-moivth disease\nbeeing tested in Argentina, the\nvaccine having been prepared by\ntreating blood from ,i flee ted ani\nmals with crystal violet dye.\n1\nWill Take\nBills By Mid-\n(Prepared by Congressman Frances P. Bolton's\nWashington Office in her absence)\n\u00a3*0NGRESS is hard at it, though\nno legislation can be ready for\nthe House to take up prior to the\nmiddle of Sep\ntember. This is\nalso true of the\nS e n a e o\nmittees are\ns u y i n s u\nimportant mat\nters as down\nward revision of\na ropriations\nwhich have been\nmade for war\na e n i e s u\ne o y e n\no e nsation\nproposals, re\nvi-\nNative leaders forced the issue\nat the time the present law was\nenacted. The Philippine situation\nis not helped any by the fact that\neight of our government agencies\nare operating there with no single\nhead or coordinated effort.\nr*REATER CLEVELAND is aot\nto be as hard hit on unem\nployment as many other cities, ac\ncording to government authorities.\nExcept for the Akron area, north\neastern Ohio is not expected to\nsuffer as high a percentage of un\nemployment as other parts sf\nOhio.\nThese sources predict that du|t\ning the next six or eight weeks\nthe Ohio cities with greatest pro\nportionate unemployment will be\nAkron, Sandusky, Toledo, Lima,\nDayton, Springfield and Cincinnati.\n6y GENE\n\u00abSeBrr-i\n**40e's Cot It* SoftI Ktcpm' Cool Carrytn' Ids\n*4%\nUp\nSeptember\nagencies by law, termination dates\nwere written in, so there is a defi\nnite legal basis for action in those\ninstances. Where the President\nacted by executive order, he did so\nin some cases as Commander-i\u00bb*\nChief and with no mention of\ntermination or time limits. Sines\nthe President is Commander-ia\nChief in peace as well as in war.\na legal problem arises which must\nbe worked out carefully.\nE N A O V A N E E\nCARft\nbbssst\u00e4\n'3\n\u00bb\u00bbMae\u00bb\n'8\nsuggestion of a labor-managt\nment \"peace\" conference is beat\ning fruit. The President has had\nthe heads of the \"Big Four\"\u2014the\nheads of the U. S. Chamber of\nCommerce, National Association\nof Manufacturers, American Fed\neration of Labor and the Congress\nof Industrial Organization to\ngether a time or two, and they are\nworking out an agenda for the\nproposed general labor-manage\nmerit conference to be held later\nin the year. If and when the con\nference materializes, it will be\nbarometer by which forecasters\nwill gauge future labor-nuuiaco\nment relations.\n\"ENORMER High 'CommlssTonsr\nPaul McNutt has reported to\nthe President on the Philippines.\nDetails are not known, but the\nreport is thought to cover some\nrather alarming conditions which\nwill strengthen the general opiS\nion that to give the Islands their\nindependence next July as pro\nvided by. existing statute would ha\ndangerous.\ni\n-'ai","height":"27054","width":"21363"}}
